{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17507616","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17507616"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:55:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:55:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2647"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2647","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2647"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.48,0.22,0.24,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2647"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107417"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2647","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2647"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2647"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89897"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"183"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3059"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3068"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6483"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14235"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14445"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16700"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39996"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42536"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107417","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107417"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of vomiting and diarrhoea. She has experienced fatigue, muscle aches, and 5 kg weight loss over the past few weeks. She has no significant medical history other than hypertension. Her only regular medication is olmesartan.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell and confused. Her pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 90/50 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.0\u00b0C. Her cardiorespiratory examination is normal. Her abdomen is diffusely tender with guarding. She has received 1.5 L of normal saline from paramedics without improvement in her blood pressure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EArterial blood gas results show:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EpH 7.18 (7.35-7.45)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EPaO2 80 mmHg (80-100)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EPaCO2 28 mmHg (35-45)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EK 3.4 mmol/L (3.5-4.9)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ENa 129 mmol/L (137-145)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ECl 102 mmol/L (100-109)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EHCO3 19 mmol/L (22-32)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ECa2+ 2.7 mmol/L (2.2-2.6)\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following would best explain her clinical picture?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Excessive chloride administration","Addison\u0027s disease","Gastroenteritis","Renal tubular acidosis","Acetazolamide"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s presentation is most consistent with an Addisonian crisis, also known as acute adrenal insufficiency. The key features supporting this diagnosis are intractable hypotension unresponsive to fluid resuscitation, normal anion gap metabolic acidosis (NAGMA), hyponatraemia, and hypercalcaemia. The anion gap is 8 mmol/L (calculated as Na - Cl - HCO3 = 129 - 102 - 19 = 8, or 11.4 if including K+), which falls within the normal range of 8-16 mmol/L (4-13 mmol/L if K+ not included). While hyperkalaemia is typically associated with Addison\u0027s disease, this patient\u0027s potassium is slightly low, likely due to gastrointestinal losses from vomiting and diarrhoea.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAddison\u0027s disease\u003C/strong\u003E best explains the entire clinical picture. The patient is likely experiencing an adrenal crisis, precipitated by acute gastroenteritis. This explains the intractable hypotension (due to cortisol and aldosterone deficiency), NAGMA (due to mineralocorticoid deficiency), hyponatraemia (due to aldosterone deficiency), and hypercalcaemia (due to cortisol deficiency). The recent history of fatigue, muscle aches, and weight loss are also consistent with the chronic progression of Addison\u0027s disease before the acute crisis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExcessive chloride administration\u003C/strong\u003E can indeed lead to NAGMA through hyperchloraemic acidosis. However, this wouldn\u0027t explain the patient\u0027s hypotension, hyponatraemia, or hypercalcaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGastroenteritis\u003C/strong\u003E alone, resulting in diarrhoea and vomiting, could cause NAGMA through bicarbonate loss and could explain some of the electrolyte abnormalities. However, it wouldn\u0027t account for the intractable hypotension or the degree of metabolic derangement seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERenal tubular acidosis\u003C/strong\u003E can cause NAGMA, but the mechanism is more complex and wouldn\u0027t explain the other clinical features, particularly the hypotension.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcetazolamide\u003C/strong\u003E, a carbonic anhydrase inhibitor, can prevent bicarbonate generation leading to NAGMA. However, it doesn\u0027t account for the other clinical and biochemical findings in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EManagement of an Addisonian crisis involves immediate administration of intravenous hydrocortisone, along with fluid and electrolyte replacement. Once the patient is stabilised, further investigations including a morning cortisol level and ACTH stimulation test can be performed to confirm the diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Intractable hypotension and normal anion gap metabolic acidosis are key features of an Addisonian crisis.","Addisonian crisis can present with hyponatraemia, hyperkalaemia (though may be normal or low due to gastrointestinal losses), and hypercalcaemia.","Addisonian crisis is often precipitated by acute illness such as gastroenteritis."],"references":["Farkas J. Adrenal Crisis. Vermont, USA: The Internet Book of Critical Care; 2017 [cited 2021 June 28]. Available at: https://emcrit.org/ibcc/adrenal-crisis/","Nickson, C. Normal Anion gap Metabolic acidosis In: Life in the fast lane [online]. 2020 [Cited 2021 June 28]. Available at: https://litfl.com/normal-anion-gap-metabolic-acidosis/."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89897"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2647"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89897","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89897"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-29T20:55:05+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-29T20:56:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2647"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107417"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"at